sentence: U.S. stocks rose on Tuesday, but faded into the close.
It’s a pattern stocks have followed on several up days over the past few weeks, continuing a volatile stretch in the thick of third-quarter earnings season and ahead of the November election.
Investors awaited news on the last day of talks on fiscal stimulus to boost the U.S. economy ahead of a self-imposed deadline.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed up 113 points, or 0.4%, after having been up more than 300 points earlier in the day.
It’s the third session in a row that has seen selling into the close.
The S&P 500 gained 0.5% and the Nasdaq Composite climbed 0.3%.
The Nasdaq’s rise comes after five straight declines for the tech-heavy index.
Several notable companies reported earnings on Tuesday morning, including Procter & Gamble (ticker: PG) and Lockheed Martin (LMT).
Netflix (NFLX) and Texas Instruments (TXN) are set to release results after the bell.
Economic data on Tuesday included September housing starts from the Census Bureau.
At an annualized 1.42 million units, the figure came in slightly below expectations—and August’s number was revised down—but overall the U.S. housing market remains remarkably strong.
Overseas, the Nikkei 225 slipped 0.4% and the S&P ASX 100 dropped 0.7% in Sydney on Tuesday, while the Hang Seng added 0.1% in Hong Kong.
In Europe, the Stoxx 600 index ticked down 0.4% as the German DAX lost 0.9%, the French CAC 40 fell 0.3%, and the U.K.’s FTSE 100 rose 0.1%.
U.S. stocks slumped on Monday, with the Dow dropping 410 points, after no agreement was made on fiscal stimulus talks.
A spokesperson for House Speaker Nancy Pelosi stated she hoped there would be clarity on whether a stimulus deal will be completed before the election by the end of Tuesday.
An agreement between House Democrats and the White House doesn’t guarantee passage in the U.S. Senate.

“It really seems that neither side want to hand the other a win before the election and would prefer to blame the lack of stimulus on each other,” said Rony Nehme, chief market analyst at Squared Financial.
Another uncertainty hanging over the market, the fate of the U.K.’s trade with European Union, also saw incremental progress, with news that formal talks are likely to restart.
Investors have also been weighing rising coronavirus cases in parts of the U.S. and throughout the world, fearing more restrictions on business activity may be coming to limit the virus’ spread.
More cities and regions have rolled back reopening measures, but the kind of widespread lockdowns seen in the spring have been avoided.
Oil settled higher with the price of West Texas Intermediate crude up 1.5% and Brent crude up 1.3%.

Alphabet (GOOGL) shares added 1.4% following a Wall Street Journal report that said the Justice Department plans to file an antitrust suit against the Google parent, alleging the company engaged in anticompetitive behavior to maintain its dominance in search and advertising.
Goldman Sachs (GS) stock rose 1.1% after reports said that the bank will pay a fine of roughly $2.8 billion to settle charges related to its role in a Malaysian investment-fund scandal.
IBM (IBM) shares slid 6.5% after reporting earnings results late Monday and declining to provide forward guidance.
Logitech (LOGI) shares advanced 15.8% after reporting a strong fiscal second quarter helped by a surge in sales of webcams and gaming equipment.
Procter & Gamble shares gained 0.5% after announcing earnings ahead of the bell and topping Wall Street’s expectations.
The company, which has benefited from stay-at-home trends, also raised its fiscal 2021 outlook.
Lockheed Martin stock slipped 3% after the aerospace and defense company beat analyst estimates and raised full-year earnings guidance on Tuesday morning.
Expectations were high going into the report.
Albertsons (ACI) shares added 5.8% as the grocery chain’s earnings results came in ahead of projections thanks to households continuing to dine in and shop online for groceries.
The company reported a 243% increase in digital sales.
Parsley Energy (PE) shares jumped 5.3% after a Wall Street Journal report said Pioneer Natural Resources (PXD) is reportedly interested in acquiring the Texas shale driller.

Pioneer stock fell 4.1%
